{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Komi |image = [[File:Komi peoples.jpg|300px]] |population = approx. 553,000 (2002){{sfn|Minahan|2002a|p=1003}}{{sfn|Minahan|2002b|p=1505}} |popplace = [[Russia]], largely located in the [[Komi Republic]], [[Perm Krai]], [[Nenets Autonomous Okrug]], [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]], and [[Murmansk Oblast]] |region1 = {{flag|Russia}} |pop1 = *Komi-Zyrians 293,406 (2002), 228,235 (2010) *Komi-Permyaks 125,235 (2002), 94,456 (2010) |ref1 = <ref>{{cite web|title=Russian Census 2010. Nationalities |url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nac_02.php |website=demoscope.ru |publisher=Демоскоп Weekly |language=Russian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622084055/http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nac_02.php |archivedate=2011-06-22 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Russian Census 2002. Nationalities |url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nac_10.php |website=demoscope.ru |publisher=Демоскоп Weekly |language=Russian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/683aGZggq?url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nac_10.php |archivedate=2012-05-30 |df= }}</ref> |region2 = {{flag|Ukraine}} |pop2 = *Komi-Zyrians and Komi-Permyaks 2,710 (2001) |ref2 = <ref>{{cite web|title=National composition of population|url=http://2001.ukrcensus.gov.ua/results/nationality_population/nationality_popul1/select_5/?botton=cens_db&box=5.1W&k_t=00&p=50&rz=1_1&rz_b=2_1%20%20%20&n_page=3|website=2001.ukrcensus.gov.ua|publisher=State statistics committee of Ukraine, 2001 census|language=Ukrainian}}</ref> |region3 = {{flag|CIS}} |pop3 = *Komi-Zyrians 8,210 (1989) *Komi-Permyaks 4,791 (1989) |ref3 = <ref>{{cite web|title=Soviet Census 1989. Nationalities |url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/sng_nac_89.php |website=demoscope.ru |publisher=Демоскоп Weekly |language=Russian |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316172713/http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/sng_nac_89.php |archivedate=2010-03-16 |df= }}</ref> |region4 = {{flag|Estonia}} |pop4 = *Komi-Zyrians and Komi-Permyaks 95 <small>(2011)</small> |ref4 = <ref>[http://pub.stat.ee/px-web.2001/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=RL0428&ti=RAHVASTIK+RAHVUSE%2C+SOO+JA+ELUKOHA+J%C4RGI%2C+31%2E+DETSEMBER+2011&path=../Database/Rahvaloendus/REL2011/07Rahvastiku_demograafilised_ja_etno_kultuurilised_naitajad/08Rahvus_Emakeel_ja_keelteoskus_Murded/&lang=2 RL0428: Rahvastik rahvuse, soo ja elukoha järgi, 31. detsember 2011]</ref> |rels = {{Plainlist| * Predominantly '''† [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]]''' * ([[Russian Orthodox Church]]) * also [[Shamanism]] }} |langs = [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Komi language|Komi]] |related-c = [[Udmurts]], other [[Uralic peoples]] }} The '''Komi''' are a [[Uralic peoples|Uralic]] ethnic group whose homeland is in the north-east of [[European Russia]] around the basins of the [[Vychegda]], [[Pechora River|Pechora]] and [[Kama river|Kama]] rivers. They mostly live in the [[Komi Republic]], [[Perm Krai]], [[Murmansk Oblast]], [[Khanty–Mansi Autonomous Okrug]], and [[Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug]] in the Russian Federation.
The Komi belong to the Permian branch of the [[Finno-Ugric peoples]] and are divided into eight sub-groups.{{sfn|Minahan|2002a|p=1003}} Their northernmost sub-group is also known as the [[Komi-Izhemtsy]] (from the name of the river [[Izhma River|Izhma]]) or [[Iz'vataz]]. This group numbers 15,607 (2002). This group is distinct for its more traditional, strongly subsistence based economy which includes [[reindeer]] husbandry. Komi-Permyaks (125,235 people) live in [[Perm Krai]] and [[Kirov Oblast]] of Russia.{{sfn|Minahan|2002b|p=1505}}
==Name== There have been at least three names for the Komis: ''Permyaks'', ''Zyrians'' ({{lang-rus|пермяки, зыряне}}) and ''Komi'', the last being the self-designation of the people.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=25}}
The name '''Permyaks''' firstly appeared in the 10th century in Russian sources and came from the ancient name of the land between the [[Mezen River]] and [[Pechora River]] – ''Perm'' or "''[[Great Perm]]''" ({{lang-ru|Пермь Великая}}).{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=17-20}} Several origins of the name have been proposed but the most accepted is from [[Veps language|Veps]] ''Peräma'' "back, outer or far-away land" from Veps ''perä'' "back, extreme" and ''ma'' "land". In [[Old Norse]] and Old English it was known as ''[[Bjarmaland]]'' and ''Beormas'' respectively{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=19}} but those Germanic names might designate some other place than the Russian ''Perm''.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=20}} Since the 20th century the name has been applied only to the southern Komi (Komi-Permyaks) in Perm Krai.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=20}} In Russian ''permyak'' also means "an inhabitant of Perm or Perm Krai" independently from ethnicity.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=20}}
The name for the northern Komis – '''Zyrians''' – has a more contradictory origin. It exists since the 14th century and it had many different forms in various Russian sources such as ''Seryan, Siryan, Syryan, Suryan'' and ''Ziryan, Zyryan'' ({{lang-ru|серьяне, сирьяне, сыряне, суряне, зиряне, зыряне}}), but the latter finally became predominant.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=20-25}} Turkin believed that it may come from a small local tribe of the Komis (probably named ''saran'') which first met the Russians hence the name became default for all the northern Komis.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=24-25}} The neighbour Finno-Uralic people call the Komis with similar names: Khanty ''sərän, sərån, săran, sārån'', Mansi ''sarän'', Nenets ''sānnğr, saran'', Udmurt ''sara-kum''.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|p=23}}
The name '''Komi''' is the endonym for all groups of the people. It was first recorded by ethnographers in the 18th century.{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=25-26}} It originates from the Finno-Ugric word meaning "man, human": Komi ''kom'', Udmurt ''kum'', Mansi ''kom, kum'', Khanty ''xum'', Selkup ''qum'', Hungarian ''hím'' "male".{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=25-26}} The origin from the name of the [[Kama River]] is disproved{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=25-26}} though some scholars (like Paula Kokkonen{{sfn|Taagepera|1999|p=301}}) favour this version.
== Subgroups == [[File:Komi people area in Northern Russia map.svg|thumbnail| {{legend|tomato|Komi-Zyrians}} {{legend|gold|Komi of the [[Izhma River]]}} {{legend|magenta|Komi-Permyaks}} {{legend|blue|Komi of the [[Yazva River]]}} {{legend|turquoise|Komi of the Upper [[Kama River]] (Zyuzdino or [[Afanasyevsky District|Afanasyevo]]), nearly fully assimilated}}]] Komi people are divided into two main groups and several smaller subgroups. The Komi have been traditionally named after the rivers where they live: *Komi-Zyrians<ref>While the name "Zyrian" is generally considered outdated, some members of the ethnic group prefer it, considering "Komi" to imply greater [[Russification]]; see Marjorie Mandelstam Balzer, ''The Tenacity of Ethnicity: A Siberian Saga in Global Perspective'' ([[Princeton University Press]], 1999; {{ISBN|0-691-00673-3}}), p. 238, n. 8.{{Dubious||reason=A very-very dubious statement, "Komi" has been a self designation|date=July 2015}}</ref> **[[Izhma Komi|Komi-Izhma]] of the [[Izhma River]] (Komi reindeer herders) ***Komi of the [[Kola Peninsula]] ***Komi of [[Nenets Autonomous Okrug]] ***Komi of the Lower [[Ob River|Ob]] and [[Lyapin River]]s **Komi of the [[Vashka River|Vashka]] and [[Mezen River]]s **Komi of the [[Vym River]] **Komi of the Lower [[Ob River]] **Komi of the [[Pechora River]] **Komi of the [[Vychegda River]] **Komi of the [[Sysola River]] **Komi of the [[Letka River|Letka]] and [[Luza River]]s *Komi-Permyaks **Komi of the Yazva River **Komi of the Upper Kama River (nearly fully assimilated into Russians)
==Language== The [[Komi language]] belongs to the [[Permic languages|Permian branch]] of the [[Uralic languages|Uralic family]]. There is limited mutual intelligibility with Udmurt.{{sfn|Taagepera|1999|p=310}} There are two main dialects: [[Komi-Zyrian language|Zyrian]] and [[Komi-Permyak language|Permyak]]. Until the 18th century, Komi was written in the [[Old Permic script|Old Permic]] alphabet introduced by [[Saint Stephen of Perm]] in the 14th century. [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] was used from the 19th century and briefly replaced by the Latin alphabet between 1929 and 1933. The Komi language is currently written in Cyrillic, adding two extra letters - Іі and Ӧӧ - to represent vowel sounds which do not exist in Russian. The first book to be printed in Komi (a vaccination manual) appeared in 1815.{{sfn|Taagepera|1999|p=313}}
==Religious beliefs== Most Komis belong to the [[Russian Orthodox Church]], but their religion often contains traces of pre-Christian beliefs (see [[Komi mythology]]). A large number of Komis are [[Old Believers]].{{sfn|Minahan|2002a|p=1004}}
==History== Based on [[linguistic reconstruction]], the prehistoric [[Permians]] are assumed to have split into two peoples during the first millennium BC: the Komis and the [[Udmurts]].{{sfn|Minahan|2002a|p=1004}} By the 16th-17th centuries, the Komis further divided into the Komi-Permyaks (who remained in the [[Kama River]] basin) and the Komi-Zyrians (who migrated north).{{sfn|Туркин|1995|pp=25-26}}
From the 12th century the Russians began to expand into the Perm region and the Komis came into contact with [[Novgorod Republic|Novgorod]]. Novgorodian traders travelled to the region in search of furs and animal hides.<ref>''Parlons Komi'' pp.113–114</ref> The Novgorodians referred to the southern Komi region as "the [[Great Perm]]". Komi dukes unified the Great Perm with its centre at the stronghold of [[Cherdyn, Perm Krai|Cherdyn]]. As the Middle Ages progressed, Novgorod gave way to Moscow as the leading Russian power in the region.{{sfn|Taagepera|1999|p=299}} In 1365, [[Dmitry Donskoy]], Prince of Moscow, gave [[Stephen of Perm]] the task of converting the region to Christianity. Stephen's mission led to the creation of the [[eparchy]] of Perm in 1383 and, after his death, Stephen became the patron saint of the Komis. He also devised an [[Old Permic script|alphabet for the Komi language]].<ref>''Parlons Komi'' pp.114–115</ref> Nevertheless, some Komis resisted Christianisation, notably the shaman Pama. The Duke of Perm only accepted baptism in 1470 (he was given the Christian name Mikhail), possibly in an attempt to stave off Russian military pressure in the region. Mikhail's conversion failed to stop an attack by Moscow which seized Cherdyn in 1472. Mikhail was allowed to keep his title of duke but was now a vassal of Moscow. The duchy only survived until 1505 when Mikhail's son Matvei was replaced by a Russian governor and Komi independence came to an end.{{sfn|Taagepera|1999|pp=300-301}}
In the 1500s many Russian migrants began to move into the region, beginning a long process of colonisation and attempts at assimilating the Komis. [[Syktyvkar]] (''Ust-Sysolsk'' before 1930) was founded as the chief Russian city in the region in the 18th century. The Russian government established penal settlements in the north for criminals and political prisoners. There were several Komi rebellions in protest against Russian rule and the influx of Slav settlers, especially after large numbers of freed serfs arrived in the region from the 1860s. A national movement to revive Komi culture also emerged.{{sfn|Minahan|2002a|p=1005}}<ref>''Parlons Komi'' p.115</ref>
Russian rule in the area collapsed after [[World War I]] and the [[Russian Revolution (1917)|revolutions of 1917]].{{fact|date=August 2017}} In the subsequent [[Russian Civil War]], the [[Bolsheviks]] fought the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] for control of the region.{{fact|date=August 2017}} The Allied interventionist forces encouraged the Komis to set up their own independent state with the help of political prisoners freed from the local penal colonies.{{fact|date=August 2017}} After the Allies withdrew in 1919, the Bolsheviks took over. They promoted Komi culture but increased industrialisation damaged the Komis' traditional way of life. [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]'s purges of the 1930s devastated the Komi intelligentsia, who were accused of "bourgeois nationalism". The remote and inhospitable region was also regarded as an ideal location for the prison camps of the [[Gulag]]. The influx of political prisoners and the rapid industrialisation of the region as a result of [[World War II]] left the Komis a minority in their own lands. Stalin carried out further purges of the Komi intellectual class in the 1940s and 1950s, and Komi language and culture was suppressed. Since the end of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Komis have reasserted their claims to a separate identity.{{sfn|Minahan|2002a|pp=1005–1008}}
== Genetics == A study on north-eastern-european populations, published in March 2013, found that Komi-Zyrians form a distinct pole of genetic diversity.<ref name=plosone130307>{{cite web | url = http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0058552 | title = A Genome-Wide Analysis of Populations from European Russia Reveals a New Pole of Genetic Diversity in Northern Europe | first = Andrey V. | last = Khrunin | publisher = PLOS One | date = 7 March 2013 }}</ref>
